<TEXT>
united press international says it lost 16 
million in 1988 and it is laying off about 40 employees 
president paul steinle said tuesday that the 1988 loss was down 
substantially from a 25 million shortfall in 1987 and that he 
expects the 81yearold news agency to begin turning a profit by the 
end of this year 
steinle said about onethird of upis losses in 1988 resulted 
from onetime costs involving the olympics political conventions 
elections and staff severance payments 
the upi president said in a statement that some 40 positions were 
being eliminated worldwide although the statement did not give a 
breakdown upi staffers speaking on condition of anonymity said 20 
of the jobs were in foreign bureaus and 20 were in domestic bureaus 
including 10 in washington where upi has its world headquarters 
steinle said no upi services were being eliminated and that he 
expected that about 40 persons would be hired as regional business 
reporters sometime in 1989 restoring overall staffing to its 
previous level 
upi said it was combining two managing editor positions into one 
with bill ferguson former managing editor for national news 
becoming managing editor of upi news 
leon daniel who had been managing editor for international news 
since 1987 will return to reporting upi said 
</TEXT>
