<TEXT>
japans decision to retain its cap on car 
exports to the united states drew little praise in this country 
with reaction split between those who wanted the voluntary export 
quotas lowered and those who say the restraints are no longer useful 
two of the big three us automakers ford motor co and chrysler 
corp welcomed the decision announced tuesday in tokyo while 
chrysler said the restraints were needed to keep the us auto 
industry healthy ford broadened its justification for the quotas by 
saying they should remain in place until the united states has 
approached trade equity with japan in products ranging from steel 
and textiles to semiconductors 
general motors corp called the quotas irrelevant in a market 
where japanese makers have consistently shipped fewer cars than the 
number allowed by their government 
the extension is almost symbolic gm said the quotas 
are not constraining shipments from japan and are not expected to 
under current market conditions 
japans minister of international trade and industry hiroshi 
mitsuzuka said tuesday in tokyo that japan would continue to limit 
car exports to the united states to 23 million vehicles annually 
and predicted shipments in fiscal year ending next march would fall 
100000 vehicles short of the quota 
he said the decision to continue the voluntary restraints was 
taken out of concern that uninhibited car exports would trigger 
protectionist sentiment in the united states 
japan unilaterally adopted the quotas in 1981 as a way to dampen 
calls for legal restrictions on imports of asian cars 
the action came amid a deep depression in the us auto industry 
high gasoline prices that steered car buyers from detroits larger 
products to more fuel efficient smaller cars and a strong dollar 
that gave imports a price advantage over domestic products 
the auto industry has since recovered its strength in part 
through adopting japanesestyle production methods and as gasoline 
prices have dropped the publics taste has swung back toward larger 
vehicles made by detroit 
also the dollar has been sharply devalued against the yen 
forcing japanese automakers to raise dollar prices to cover their 
production and shipping costs 
the shifting marketplace has altered the nature of the quotas 
from a policy that protects us makers to one that increases their 
competition said david healy automotive analyst with the new york 
brokerage house of drexel burnham lambert 
the japanese being smart businessmen have gotten around the 
quotas in many ways he said one is to build more cars in the 
united states more domestic competition 
another is to ship more expensive cars to the united states 
since the quotas are based on the number of vehicles not their 
dollar value healy said 
the japanese announcement did little to appease the chairman of 
the house energy and commerce committee rep john dingell dmich 
who said the quota fixes the number so high it really doesnt 
matter 
the united auto workers union praised the japanese decision while 
expressing disappointment that the quotas had not been made more 
stringent 
as usual the current administration was of no assistance in 
persuading the japanese to renew the quotas said uaw president 
owen bieber 
japans trade deficit with the united states totalled 598 
billion in 1987 japanese companies made 733000 cars in the united 
states last year through november 232 percent more than in the 
corresponding period a year earlier 
</TEXT>
