parliament today enacted two key laws 
giving citizens the right to demonstrate and to join political 
parties other than the communist party the sole legal party in 
hungary since it took power in 1948 
the new law on association however only grants political 
parties and new independent movements the right to exist a separate 
law to be passed later this year will regulate the registration and 
operation of political parties according to officials 
only then will two fledgling political parties and the dozens of 
independent political groups formed in recent months be able to 
field candidates for parliament and for local councils 
the longawaited laws on assembly and assocation were passed with 
an overwhelming majority in parliament a day after advocates of 
greater pluralism clashed with more orthodox communists over the 
pace of reform 
of the 387 deputies in communistruled hungary only six opposed 
the law on association and just seven voted against the law on 
assembly 
the debate on the two laws which pitted reformers against 
communist party conservatives was overshadowed by the announcement 
tuesday that the withdrawal of soviet troops from hungarian 
territory would begin soon 
defense minister ferenc karpati said the withdrawal of an armored 
division an air force battalion and several air force units could 
be completed soon possibly before the end of the year 
communist party leader karoly grosz was quoted by hungarian media 
as having told a japanese newspaper that withdrawal was only a 
matter of weeks away 
karpatis remarks came as parliament adopted by an overwhelming 
majority a constitutional amendments including one that will 
facilitate the introduction of an alternative civilian service for 
conscientious objectors 
justice minister kalman kulcsar told the legislature the bills 
adopted today laid down the fundamental rights of citizens to 
assemble and to form associations including political parties the 
house however did pass a measure banning demonstrations outside 
parliament 
