for six years the legislature has refused to limit lawsuits to 
only the most seriously injured lobbyists for the legal profession 
contend such limits will strip victims of their right to sue in 
exchange for a savings of only 100 per car 
auto insurance rates in new jersey are among the highest in the 
nation 
the joint underwriting association a statebacked agency created 
under the kean administration in 1983 to cover drivers unable to 
purchase coverage in the private market is staggering under a 
deficit of more than 25 billion 
to keep the jua afloat all of the states more than 4 million 
drivers pay an average of 220 per car in annual surcharges 
a series of reforms took effect jan 1 to contain rising rates by 
increasing deductibles requiring accident victims to pay part of 
their medical costs and imposing a fee schedule on how much doctors 
may charge 
the reforms also allow drivers to limit their right to sue in 
exchange for lower premiums but kean has said such an option is 
inadequate 
i was shocked its like he was looking for something dramatic 
to round out his speech said michael m rossi iii president of 
the independent insurance agents of new jersey we just went 
through a long arduous task of legislative wheeling and dealing and 
now were seeing the beginning of that law he has to give the law a 
chance to work 
