<TEXT>
the national farmers union called wednesday on 
congress to reject a proposal to let farmers collect federal 
subsidies without regard to the kind of crops they produce 
nfu president leland swenson said the idea known as 
decoupling would be devastating for farmers and rural 
communities endanger the environment and destablize the position of 
third world farmers 
swenson told a news conference that decoupling would be a 
shortterm welfare program and will be opposed vigorously by nfu 
lobbyists 
decoupling has been around for years but has not had great 
support on capitol hill one of the early decisions by the incoming 
bush administration will be whether to embrace decoupling as a way 
of containing government farm costs 
the nfus main rival the american farm bureau federation at one 
time supported decoupling but since has backed off to give it a 
closer look 
one of the biggest advocates is the heritage foundation a 
washingtonbased conservative think tank which recently issued a 
task force report saying that one of the first jobs of the bush 
administration should be to cut subsidies and get farmers off the 
dole 
decoupling the heritage report said would allow federal 
payments to farmers to be based on a flat rate and targeted to those 
most in need as it has been for more than half a century payments 
now are pegged to specific kinds of crops and levels of production 
the larger the farm the larger the subsidy 
under decoupling farmers would simply be given a cash payment 
and then be free to grow or not grow any crop they choose 
planting decisions with decoupling would then be based on 
market signals consumer demand for a product rather than on what 
is required by washington the heritage report said 
swenson also released a report analyzing a decoupling bill 
introduced by sen rudy boschwitz rminn in 1985 as the family 
farm protection and full production act he said the bill continues 
to have some support in congress along with backing from big grain 
companies such as cargill inc 
its really a copout in addressing the real issue of adopting 
and implementing a farm program which enhances the market price for 
agricultural commodities swenson said it implies that the 
family farm structure of agricuture is not important 
the analysis used figures attributed to the institute for trade 
and agricultrure st paul minn showing that the boschwitz bill 
would reduce federal price support loans sharply for major crops 
including wheat to 160 per bushel from 206 this year and corn 
to 130 per bushel from the 1989 rate of 165 
lowering of world prices a result of decoupling would 
aggravate the situation of third world farmers who are our best 
potential customers for us food exports swenson said 
the nfu he said will draft its own alternative to decoupling to 
assure consumers an adequate and dependable supply of food and 
enhance the market price of agricultural commodities 
although swenson did not disclose details of what nfus plan 
might include he said it would reduce the budget impact of farm 
programs and allow for a continued expansion of agricultural 
exports 
the 1988 drought helped siphon off huge stockpiles of us grain 
boosting market prices for wheat to an average of 389 per bushel 
last month from 270 a year earlier corn in december according to 
the agriculture department averaged 254 per bushel compared to 
the yearearlier mark of 172 per bushel 
swenson was asked if the nfu would recommend an increase in 
federal price supports to as much as current market prices he 
replied or higher 
the reagan administration for eight years has been committed to a 
marketoriented farm policy less reliance on federal controls and 
freer world trade those ideals are expected to continue under the 
bush administration 
but swenson is not convinced at this time that foreign countries 
will go along with current us agricultural trade objectives in the 
bush administration than they have in the reagan years 
there isnt such a thing as a free market swenson said it 
doesnt exist will not exist either in this country or any other 
major exporting country in the world 
</TEXT>
