<TEXT>
surgeon general c everett koop on wednesday 
urged americans to continue the gains made over the last 25 years in 
the fight against smoking by aiming efforts at women young people 
and others likely to pick up the habit 
koop said the decline in the proportion of american smokers from 
40 percent of the population in 1965 to 29 percent in 1987 was a 
revolution in smoking behavior 
but he said the fact that 50 million americans still smoke that 
women are quitting more slowly than men and that young people are 
continuing to start presents enormous challenges in continuing the 
downward trend in smoking 
koop spoke at a news conference at which he issued a new 
government report on smoking that documents changes that have 
occurred in the 25 years since the surgeon general first declared 
cigarette smoking caused cancer and death 
he said antismoking campaigns have educated the public about the 
hazards of smoking and a growing number of states communities and 
businesses are enacting smoking restrictions but more efforts are 
needed he said 
during the next quarter century and beyond progress will be 
slow and smokingrelated mortality will remain high unless the 
health community more effectively reaches children and adolescents 
women minorities and bluecollar workers he said in the report 
meanwhile the tobacco institute the tobacco industrys lobbying 
organization was running fullpage ads in major newspapers around 
the country this week supporting smokers and declaring enough is 
enough 
the ads said there has been enough taxation legislation 
control censorship harassment and discrimination directed against 
smokers 
koop discounted the institutes claims including its point that 
smokers pay 10 billion in cigarette taxes which the lobbying group 
called more than their fair share koop said that adds up to 
only 30 percent of the direct health costs the government pays to 
take care of smokingrelated illnesses and disabilities 
he added the tobacco people should begin to discriminate 
against advertising to the very people who have the highest problem 
with smoking namely teenagers and those in minority groups and 
those who are bluecollar workers 
instead he said cigarette manufacturers appear to be aiming 
many of their ads at young people to lure them into the smoking 
habit 
if you look at advertising now compared to 15 years ago youll 
find that the models have gotten extraordinarily young beautiful 
chic sophisticated and sexy and if that isnt something that isnt 
appealing to young people i dont know what is 
figures in koops report showed that antismoking efforts have 
been most successful in getting men to quit half of all men smoked 
in 1965 but by 1987 less than a third were lighting up 
women smokers declined from 32 percent to 27 percent over the 
period the report said 
the figures also show a slow decline over the period among blacks 
and bluecollar workers and virtually no change among those who 
never graduated from high school 
among high school seniors daily cigarette smoking dropped from 
29 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980 and then leveled off in the 
1821 percent range for the seven years after that 
 
</TEXT>
