<TEXT>
support for civil rights measures and steps to 
assist the poor are growing nationwide according to a survey of 
racial attitudes released wednesday 
americans do have a conscience pollster louis harris told a 
news conference in unveiling the survey taken by his organization on 
behalf of the naacp legal defense and educational fund 
he said surveys began to find an increase in support for civil 
rights measures such as the busing of pupils to achieve school 
integration as early as 1986 the latest poll said opposition to 
busing has dropped to 54 percent among all americans after hovering 
at 78 percent for three decades 
it found 57 percent of whites opposed to busing but said that 
for the first time 51 percent of whites favor it when the buses 
carry pupils to top quality schools in the inner city and blacks to 
equally good schools outside their neighborhoods 
the survey found that 93 percent of whites and 95 percent of 
blacks favored special school programs beginning at age 8 to 
motivate poor youngsters to stay in school 
it said 90 percent of whites and 95 percent of blacks favored 
setting up federal camps where poor young people could learn 
reading writing and other skills similar majorities supported 
business incentives to provide jobs in poor neighborhoods 
seventynine percent of blacks and 81 percent of whites said the 
best longterm way to combat crime was not to spend large sums of 
money sending criminals to prison and keeping them there a long 
time but to spend the same money attacking the causes of crime 
such as reducing poverty keeping young people in school and 
motivating young people to succeed rather than become criminals 
the poll was taken june 3 through sept 12 by louis harris and 
associates and was based on interviews with more than 3000 people 
harris said that the error margin was plus or minus 2 percent 
the new yorkbased naacp legal defense and educational fund inc 
was founded in 1940 by the national association for the advancement 
of colored people but is now a separate and distinct organization 
it has been a part of many major civil rights court battles in 
recent decades and for the last 12 years has also campaigned in the 
legislative arena 
the survey demonstrates that the public is primed for 
presidential action and leadership on racerelations issues said 
elaine jones deputy directorcounsel of the organization the 
missing ingredient is strong leadership thats what we look to the 
new administration to provide 
she was critical of the reagan administrations record but added 
that there is reason to hope that the inauguration of george bush 
will usher in a new approach to civil rights at the white house and 
in the justice department 
julius chambers the groups directorcounsel said the study 
titled the unfinished agenda on race in america demonstrates 
there is a solid base of support for change 
on issue after issue blacks and whites agree that active 
leadership is needed to bring about real equality between the 
races he said 
</TEXT>
