<TEXT>
iranian president ali khamenei on 
wednesday ordered lifting on some controls over foreign trade in a 
move that may further bolster the resurgent private sector in irans 
postwar economy 
the official islamic republic news agency monitored in nicosia 
quoted khamenei as saying the commerce ministry should ease its grip 
on the economy and hand over some responsibilities such as trade 
to the people 
our brave smart and mature people are not lacking anything and 
can do the job themselves khamenei said in a reference to the 
private sector 
the ministry controls more than 80 percent of irans trade 
the government has been relaxing the tight controls imposed 
during its eightyear war with iraq the two sides signed a 
ceasefire in august 
the cashstrapped government has been trying to attract private 
funds to pay for imports to ease shortages widespread corruption in 
the governments bloated bureaucracy is also believed to be a reason 
for easing state control 
a heated debate over the economy has dragged on for years and 
polarized irans leadership into pragmatists led by khamenei and 
parliament speaker hashemi rafsanjani and hardliners such as prime 
minister hussein musavi 
the huge task of postwar reconstruction has brought the 
differences into sharp focus moves by the pragmatists to relax 
political and social restrictions as well as economic restraints 
have intensified the wrangles 
khamenei is backed by a wealthy merchant class known as 
bazaaris who largely financed the 1979 revolution which brought to 
power the islamic regime under ayatollah ruhollah khomeini the 
merchants have pushed for a more laissezfaire economy 
musavi under fire for his economic policies during the war 
seeks wider state control as he says to lessen the gap between 
rich and poor 
the government last month listed about 40 scarce items that could 
be privately imported for a trial period of two years they ranged 
from medical equipment and agricultural products to pens and books 
acting commerce minister abdolhassan vahhaji said more items will 
be deregulated he said that with the implementation of this plan 
the prices of goods will come down and it will create economic calm 
and stability 
</TEXT>
