<TEXT>
two pamunkey indian sisters are asking a 
tribal council to change a tribal law that bans them from living on 
the reservation they grew up on because they married outside the 
tribe 
kim taylor and cam porter whose grandfather was chief of the 
pamunkey for 42 years want to find land on the reservation to build 
homes and raise families but because the 23yearold twins recently 
married white men theyve been asked to leave the 1250acre 
reservation nestled in a bend of the pamunkey river in southern king 
william county 
thats the way the law reads said william swift eagle 
miles the current pamunkey chief who favors changing the law 
i want to live here mrs taylor said in a recent interview 
its a special place for me ive got a lot of family and were 
all real close part of me belongs here this is my land really my 
land 
this is where i grew up added her sister this is home 
the sisters have crusaded to have the tribal law changed 
gathering signatures from pamunkey women from as far away as 
philadelphia 
according to tribal law pamunkey women who marry outside the 
tribe give up their right to live on the reservation men in the 
tribe never lose that right white women may live on the reservation 
with their husbands although like the pamunkey women they have no 
say in the tribes government 
only about 60 people live on the reservation one of two 
remaining in virginia all but a handful are retired and the elders 
worry about the tribes future 
despite financial incentives such as paying no property tax and 
not having to buy the land one lives on its hard to keep young 
people on the reservation the nearest town is 15 miles away and 
its 40 miles to richmond where about a dozen residents commute to 
work daily 
miles said the law banning white husbands is having a drastic 
effect on the reservation population the mattaponi indians who 
live on a much smaller reservation nearby have a similar rule on 
the books but it is not strictly enforced said mattaponi chief 
walter custalow and the reservation is crowded with young families 
one problem miles said is that most of the older pamunkey had 
daughters and most of those girls married outside the tribe 
whether out of preference or necessity 
they want you to marry a pamunkey indian said mrs taylor 
thats impossible theyre all girls or theyre my cousins 
miles said he doesnt know how councilmen will vote at thurday 
nights meeting i think i can convince them he said i have 
some pretty strong arguments we have some oldtimers here and i 
think it will be close 
the sisters say theyve been been aware of the law since they 
were children if i dated a white guy i used to say i cant 
marry you cause i want to live on the reservation said mrs 
porter but you cant help who you fall in love with i just 
figured wed change the law 
mrs taylor said many of their female relatives who married 
outside the tribe would come back to the reservation if the law were 
changed she said the two have collected about 20 signatures on 
their petition and that the drive was going slowly because many 
tribe members are farflung and some of the older indians oppose the 
change 
however the sisters cause has won the support of a few 
influential tribe members including miles and their grandfather 
the former chief 
i think they realize they dont have much choice mrs taylor 
said there will be no reservation 
miles says he will bring up the issue at the next meeting of the 
tribe later this month he expects opposition from the oldtimers 
but thinks theyll come around eventually if only out of necessity 
if we dont change that were going to disappear he said 
