<DOCNO> AP890111-0276 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the european monetary system has gone 
for two years without a realignment in currency values despite 
sharp dollar movements and analysts see no quick end to its 
stability 
the system that maintains stable exchange rates between european 
currencies turns 10 years old in march it has been realigned 11 
times but not once since jan 12 1987 showing the system is 
gaining stability against a volatile dollar 
the ems is moving into a new phase said steven bell chief 
economist for morgan grenfell amp co ltd in london the first few 
years were fairly disruptive and chaotic but the realignments have 
been getting smaller 
anne vleminckx of belgiums generale de banque sa echoing the 
views of other analysts said a realignment may occur in the first 
half of 1989 but that it would be easily digested by the markets it 
might be almost a nonevent she said 
the european monetary system groups eight european economic 
community currencies those of west germany the netherlands 
france italy belgium luxembourg denmark and ireland they range 
against one another within bands that have fixed upper and lower 
limits 
if a currency exceeds its limits central banks must intervene or 
governments must take monetary action if that has no effect the 
european monetary system must be realigned 
as a rule the european monetary system faces realignment when 
either the dollar has fallen too sharply or the west german mark 
becomes too strong against the french franc west germany and france 
account for nearly half of total eec output 
the dollar defies easy prediction but the current bullish trend 
on the eve of the bush administration is reassuring european 
monetary system watchers 
a fall in the dollar normally spurs investors to put more money 
in west german marks lifting them against other european monetary 
system currencies and pushing the monetary system to the breaking 
point 
the dollars long slide from early 1985 was blamed for the 1987 
realignment but today analysts feel the threat is more likely to 
come from internal difficulties 
recently tensions usually only start when the dollar is at 
170 marks or below said reinhard kudiss an economist at the 
west german industry federation in cologne 
at the start of 1988 the european monetary system survived a 
drop in the dollar to 158 marks lately though the dollar has 
been if anything too strong not too weak on wednesday central 
banks were aggressively selling dollars and buying marks to prop up 
the west german currency 
the more difficult problem is a growing francogerman schism 
although the marks recent weakness has caused the issue to recede 
in importance economists say it could reemerge if the mark begins 
to strengthen again against the french currency 
frances booming economy has been heavily importing west german 
capital goods while germanys trade surplus with other eec countries 
is ballooning 
also west german inflation is around 15 percent against 
roughly double that for france higher inflation means french francs 
are steadily losing their real value in terms of marks 
west german officials cautious not to upset their exporters with 
a more costly mark have rejected an european monetary system 
realignment 
i think its very doubtful a realignment will be an issue in 
the foreseeable future finance minister gerhard stoltenberg said 
in late december 
bundesbank president karl otto poehl has added to that one 
must take seriously that the two most important governments within 
the ems of france and west germany do not want a realignment 
french finance minister pierre beregovoy said last week i 
flatly rule out a devaluation of the french franc 
for france a revalued mark means costlier imports and more 
inflation with local elections in march paris is unlikely to want 
to give unions reason for discontent 
yet firm denials of a realignment are ritual exercises that may 
ease but rarely kill market tension 
the trade surpluses with the rest of the eec are getting to be 
an embarrassment to the german authorities and cannot go on 
forever according to nigel rendell an economist with the london 
brokerage james capel bankers ltd 
west germanys trade surplus surged 25 percent in november to its 
secondhighest monthly surplus ever the gain came from trade with 
other eec countries while the surplus with the united states has 
been shrinking 
analysts expect a 1989 realignment if any would upgrade the 
value of the mark and the dutch guilder the other ems stalwart by 
3 to 4 percent and devalue the lira by several percentage points 
opinions varied on other currencies 
france can normally live easier with its electorate after an 
upward valuation of the mark and guilder than with a devaluation of 
the franc 
this happened in 1987 when the french and three other currencies 
were left unchanged while the mark and guilder were valued upward by 
3 percent and the belgian and luxembourg francs were valued upward 
by 2 percent 
analysts see the italian lira as a likely candidate for change in 
any realignment even though it has been unusually stable 
within the european monetary system the lira can range within 6 
percent above and below the systems parity rates for the other 
currencies that divergence is 25 percent either way 
of late the lira has traded near and at times within 225 
percent of its parity rate against the mark 
analysts said a realignment of currencies this year if any is 
not likely to occur anytime near september when the composition of 
the european currency unit is up for review the unit is based on 
the currencies of the eight european monetary system currencies plus 
the pound and the greek drachma 
</TEXT>
